\title{ospgsa: Global Sensitivity Analysis for PK-Sim / OSP models}
\description{
\code{ospgsa} performs global sensitivity analysis (GSA) of physiologically based
pharmacokinetic (PBPK) models built in PK-Sim and run through the
\href{https://www.open-systems-pharmacology.org/OSPSuite-R/}{ospsuite} package.
}
\details{
The workflow is:
\enumerate{
\item Describe the uncertain model parameters and their distributions with
\code{\link[=gsa_parameter]{gsa_parameter()}} / \code{\link[=gsa_parameters]{gsa_parameters()}}, optionally with a correlation
matrix (\code{\link[=gsa_correlation]{gsa_correlation()}}).
\item Build a model evaluator. For PK-Sim use \code{\link[=ospsuite_evaluator]{ospsuite_evaluator()}}; for
testing or non-PK-Sim GSA use \code{\link[=function_evaluator]{function_evaluator()}}.
\item Run one or more GSA methods with \code{\link[=gsa]{gsa()}} (or the building blocks
\code{\link[=gsa_delta]{gsa_delta()}}, \code{\link[=gsa_sobol]{gsa_sobol()}}, \code{\link[=gsa_morris]{gsa_morris()}}, \code{\link[=gsa_regression]{gsa_regression()}}).
\item Inspect results with \code{\link[=print]{print()}}/\code{\link[=summary]{summary()}}, \code{\link[=gsa_table]{gsa_table()}} and the
\verb{plot_*()} family (write the standard set with \code{\link[=gsa_save_plots]{gsa_save_plots()}}).
}

The main method is the Borgonovo delta moment-independent index with a
two-stage decomposition for correlated inputs (after De Carlo et al. 2023 and
Cuquerella-Gilabert et al. 2026). Sobol, Morris and regression methods are
provided for cross-checking.
}
\section{Design}{

The GSA engine (sampling, designs, estimators, plots, reports) is
model-agnostic: it only needs an evaluator that maps an input matrix to an
output matrix. PK-Sim is the first-class evaluator, but any R function can be
used, which makes the estimators testable on analytic benchmarks and reusable
for other GSA tasks.
}

